    "actor_description": "The grief isn't sharp anymore. It's weight. It sits behind my sternum and in my throat, turning everything quieter. My thoughts move slowly, like they're wading. I don't even have the energy for drama. The loss is simply there-an ache that keeps its own hours. I notice myself handling the world more gently, as if one wrong touch could make something else break. Even breathing feels careful.",
    "description_text": "{actor} carries a steady heaviness-eyes duller, movements slowed and deliberate. Their face holds sadness without spectacle; the body seems to conserve motion, as if every gesture costs more than it should.",
    "alternate_descriptions": {
        "auditory": "I hear a thick quiet-one slow breath, a small exhale that sounds like giving up on words.",
        "tactile": "Someone's presence feels weighted and still, like someone holding something they can't set down."
    },
